title: An Arrest Has Officially Been Made in the Murder of Queens Jogger Karina Vetrano
text:
Police have reportedly made an arrest in the brutal murder of a Queens jogger.
The New York Daily News reports that a 20-year-old man from East New York, has been arrested for the August 2nd sexual assault and murder of Karina Vetrano , a 30-year-old woman from Queens.
A source told NYDN that the man has no history of violent crimes, and that law enforcement focused in on him after combing reports from the neighborhoods near the scene of Vetrano’s killing.
Advertisement - Continue Reading Below The source said the suspect was linked to the victim through DNA recovered from her body.
NYDN reports that NYPD is expected to hold a Sunday news conference announcing the arrest.
This post will be updated with new information as it comes in.
Update 2/5/17, 3:15pm EST : According to NYDN , 20-year-old Brooklyn man, Chanel Lewis, has been arrested and is expected to be arraigned on murder and sexual assault charges.
The police was able to locate Lewis based on a 911 call made about his suspicious behavior in the area several months before Vetrano's murder.
"We found a 911 call prior to the homicide of him being in Howard Beach. We had a member of community call to say he was a suspicious person which we get all the time. From that we had a profile. He does have a number of summonses, he has no criminal record," said NYPD Chief of Detectives Robert Bryce.
It's not clear if anything was done about it at the time.
"This is a great day for the community and the detectives that worked day in and day out and of course it will hopefully bring some closure to the Vetrano family," Queens District Attorney Richard Brown said.
Lewis's father, a retired elementary school principal Richard Lewis, 70, told The New York Post that his son's arrest was a total shock.
"Chanel would never have gone to do what they say he has done. He’s never had a fight in his 20 years," he said.
He went on to describe his son as an honor student and "humble" kid who wanted to work in Social Services.
Vetrano's parents, Phil and Cathy, had mixed emotions at the news.
“The demon must get his justice,” Cathy told NYDN . “We will see to it.”
“I’m not going to say it is a good day but we can move forward now,” said Phil. “We know who did this.”
